WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.583
(bright music)

2
00:00:08.573 --> 00:00:10.923
<v ->So more geriatrics.</v>

3
00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:15.690
We're gonna talk some more about osteoporosis.

4
00:00:15.690 --> 00:00:16.890
We already did the gait disorders.

5
00:00:16.890 --> 00:00:18.840
We'll go into some urinary issues

6
00:00:18.840 --> 00:00:21.930
and some geriatric prevention type stuff.

7
00:00:21.930 --> 00:00:26.930
So osteoporosis, the definition, World Health Organization,

8
00:00:28.470 --> 00:00:33.040
negative 2.5 standard deviations on your T score

9
00:00:34.740 --> 00:00:36.753
is considered osteoporosis.

10
00:00:38.610 --> 00:00:41.370
Someone asked a good question before to Dr. Gary too.

11
00:00:41.370 --> 00:00:43.863
If somebody has a fragility fracture,

12
00:00:45.330 --> 00:00:47.970
a fracture from standing height, do they have osteoporosis?

13
00:00:47.970 --> 00:00:50.344
Yes, okay.

14
00:00:50.344 --> 00:00:52.770
We'll get into DEXA scanning

15
00:00:52.770 --> 00:00:54.693
a little bit here in a second too.

16
00:00:55.620 --> 00:00:58.410
But there's your cutoff you're looking for

17
00:00:58.410 --> 00:01:00.303
when you do get your DEXA scan.

18
00:01:02.430 --> 00:01:05.130
So femoral neck bone mineral density

19
00:01:05.130 --> 00:01:08.550
is the best predictor.

20
00:01:08.550 --> 00:01:10.860
The central DEXA, which most of us,

21
00:01:10.860 --> 00:01:12.150
if we just order a DEXA scan,

22
00:01:12.150 --> 00:01:15.303
that's given us the femur and the lumbar measurements,

23
00:01:16.283 --> 00:01:18.210
and yeah, fracture risk doubles

24
00:01:18.210 --> 00:01:20.463
for every one unit decrease in the T score.

25
00:01:21.390 --> 00:01:26.390
So, you think 1.5 to 2, or 2.5 to 2.5 is not a big deal.

26
00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:30.813
It actually is a pretty significant risk for the patient.

27
00:01:33.210 --> 00:01:36.300
Now, who needs bone mineral density testing?

28
00:01:36.300 --> 00:01:40.143
For your board exam, we will follow the USPSTF.

29
00:01:42.090 --> 00:01:44.680
So women, 65 and over

30
00:01:46.380 --> 00:01:48.513
should have bone mineral density testing.

31
00:01:50.040 --> 00:01:55.040
Women, 50 to 64, based on risk factors, okay?

32
00:01:55.200 --> 00:01:57.183
What are some of those risk factors?

33
00:01:58.530 --> 00:02:02.043
Smoking, alcohol use,

34
00:02:03.930 --> 00:02:07.950
chemotherapy, early menopause.

35
00:02:07.950 --> 00:02:11.400
Another thing not to forget to ask about,

36
00:02:11.400 --> 00:02:14.823
and this would be a good board question, family history.

37
00:02:16.590 --> 00:02:20.493
If mom has a hip fracture at the age of 67,

38
00:02:22.050 --> 00:02:25.143
that's somebody that's probably at elevated risk.

39
00:02:26.460 --> 00:02:28.980
They would warrant earlier screening.

40
00:02:28.980 --> 00:02:32.043
Men, RNI.

41
00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:36.000
If you were to not believe me,

42
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:37.680
and you look this up on your own today,

43
00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:40.050
plug in USPSTF osteoporosis

44
00:02:40.050 --> 00:02:42.060
in your favorite search engine,

45
00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:46.143
you will notice that this is currently being updated.

46
00:02:49.470 --> 00:02:53.973
So don't forget in your clinical practice,

47
00:02:54.870 --> 00:02:58.830
there's also men who might be heavy drinkers,

48
00:02:58.830 --> 00:03:00.780
perhaps they have advanced COPD,

49
00:03:00.780 --> 00:03:02.130
and they're getting steroids,

50
00:03:02.130 --> 00:03:04.180
or maybe they're on steroids chronically.

51
00:03:05.220 --> 00:03:08.073
Other things, people on long-term PPIs,

52
00:03:09.690 --> 00:03:12.120
those type of things increase risk.

53
00:03:12.120 --> 00:03:15.120
After Dr. Gary's lecture earlier, I made the comment to him,

54
00:03:15.120 --> 00:03:17.157
I said, "I hate hip fractures."

55
00:03:19.380 --> 00:03:21.990
They keep me awake at night, because I start looking back,

56
00:03:21.990 --> 00:03:24.603
and I think, what could we have done different?

57
00:03:26.730 --> 00:03:28.803
If somebody never has a hip fracture,

58
00:03:30.540 --> 00:03:32.040
that's hard to really prove

59
00:03:32.040 --> 00:03:36.063
that we help that good outcome, right?

60
00:03:37.650 --> 00:03:42.650
But we do, so it's devastating when this happens.

61
00:03:44.670 --> 00:03:47.070
More on the difference the USPSTF

62
00:03:47.070 --> 00:03:50.970
versus the National Osteoporosis Foundation

63
00:03:50.970 --> 00:03:55.970
and the International Society for Clinical Densitometry

64
00:03:56.430 --> 00:03:59.853
I think is what ISCD stands for.

65
00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:05.733
Somebody's gonna ask how often we do DEXA scans.

66
00:04:08.850 --> 00:04:10.140
We'll get to that.

67
00:04:10.140 --> 00:04:13.713
The ISCD folks recommend every two years.

68
00:04:15.150 --> 00:04:17.350
That's their game, right, of course they do.

69
00:04:19.710 --> 00:04:20.670
So we'll talk about that.

70
00:04:20.670 --> 00:04:22.680
We'll get to that in a second though,

71
00:04:22.680 --> 00:04:24.330
what the evidence actually shows.

72
00:04:25.740 --> 00:04:28.620
So now, first question, we got a 72-year-old woman,

73
00:04:28.620 --> 00:04:33.030
BMI of 35, sudden onset, mid-back pain.

74
00:04:33.030 --> 00:04:37.410
X-ray confirms T4 vertebral compression fracture

75
00:04:37.410 --> 00:04:39.333
and diffuse osteopenia.

76
00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:41.793
What is our next step?

77
00:04:47.910 --> 00:04:49.650
All those things in your questions,

78
00:04:49.650 --> 00:04:51.543
now remember, look for the clues.

79
00:04:53.651 --> 00:04:56.610
That's one of the few benefits of obesity.

80
00:04:56.610 --> 00:04:59.070
You're gonna have stronger bones.

81
00:04:59.070 --> 00:05:01.650
This person's a little bit younger,

82
00:05:01.650 --> 00:05:04.533
so this is a pretty abnormal location for this person.

83
00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:09.360
So this person needs to look up secondary causes,

84
00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:11.280
worried about a multiple myeloma

85
00:05:11.280 --> 00:05:13.480
or something else going on with this person.

86
00:05:14.760 --> 00:05:18.843
Primary idiopathic osteoporosis risk factors.

87
00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:28.260
Y'all know this. We'll see.

88
00:05:28.260 --> 00:05:31.230
It's gonna be really interesting with this next iteration

89
00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:34.143
of the recommendation where men fall on this,

90
00:05:35.160 --> 00:05:38.610
'cause a risk factor for hip fractures,

91
00:05:38.610 --> 00:05:40.503
compression fractures, is age.

92
00:05:42.360 --> 00:05:44.553
So at what point should men be screened?

93
00:05:46.230 --> 00:05:47.130
It really depends.

94
00:05:48.780 --> 00:05:51.993
It also really bothers me when men have hip fractures.

95
00:05:52.980 --> 00:05:55.533
I'm equal opportunity being upset in bad outcomes.

96
00:05:56.550 --> 00:05:57.383
It's not good.

97
00:05:59.610 --> 00:06:02.163
Screening for secondary causes, this person,

98
00:06:03.006 --> 00:06:06.210
in our question stem we had a second ago,

99
00:06:06.210 --> 00:06:07.380
some of these things.

100
00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:08.970
If somebody does have a fracture,

101
00:06:08.970 --> 00:06:12.000
whether it's primary or secondary,

102
00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:13.140
that's one of the few cases

103
00:06:13.140 --> 00:06:15.183
where I'll check a vitamin D level,

104
00:06:18.660 --> 00:06:22.110
and maybe treat to improve that.

105
00:06:22.110 --> 00:06:24.610
I caught a vitamin D level of three the other day,

106
00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:30.393
and a man who was there with us for a hip fracture.

107
00:06:34.950 --> 00:06:39.950
70-year-old, DEXA scan reveals lowest T score of negative 2.

108
00:06:41.640 --> 00:06:43.800
10-year fracture risk is 19%

109
00:06:43.800 --> 00:06:47.970
for major osteoporotic fracture, 5% for femur fracture.

110
00:06:47.970 --> 00:06:51.270
What's the most appropriate next step?

111
00:06:51.270 --> 00:06:55.260
Start calcium and vitamin D. Start a bisphosphonate.

112
00:06:55.260 --> 00:06:56.730
Repeat the DEXA in two years

113
00:06:56.730 --> 00:06:58.743
or repeat the DEXA in five years.

114
00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:07.050
All right, so not only do we treat

115
00:07:07.050 --> 00:07:11.070
for that negative 2.5 T score,

116
00:07:11.070 --> 00:07:15.753
we also treat based on the 10-year fracture risk.

117
00:07:18.300 --> 00:07:19.350
That's down at that bottom.

118
00:07:19.350 --> 00:07:22.350
Where I am, the DEXA scan results

119
00:07:22.350 --> 00:07:25.563
calculate the FRAX score for me, which is really nice.

120
00:07:26.940 --> 00:07:30.600
If hip fracture risk is greater than 3%

121
00:07:30.600 --> 00:07:33.840
or major osteoporotic fracture's greater than 20%,

122
00:07:33.840 --> 00:07:38.840
that's an indication for treatment, so don't miss that.

123
00:07:39.060 --> 00:07:42.240
Just 'cause their T-score is less than negative 2.5,

124
00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:43.840
they might still need treatment.

125
00:07:47.250 --> 00:07:52.250
Additionally, if somebody does have a fragility fracture,

126
00:07:52.590 --> 00:07:53.670
and they argue with you

127
00:07:53.670 --> 00:07:55.820
that they don't want to go get a DEXA scan,

128
00:07:57.711 --> 00:07:59.611
that's fine, they still need treatment

129
00:08:00.630 --> 00:08:04.413
to prevent this from happening again, to decrease the risk.

130
00:08:08.550 --> 00:08:11.310
Used to be we would say, "Wait after a fracture."

131
00:08:11.310 --> 00:08:12.690
You wanna wait a couple of months,

132
00:08:12.690 --> 00:08:16.410
'cause you worry about bone healing with bisphosphonates.

133
00:08:16.410 --> 00:08:21.150
That's less and less standard,

134
00:08:21.150 --> 00:08:23.040
and it looks like you're okay starting treatment

135
00:08:23.040 --> 00:08:25.140
a little earlier right after the fracture,

136
00:08:26.070 --> 00:08:28.290
even a couple of weeks after is probably fine.

137
00:08:28.290 --> 00:08:30.900
It's more important for that person to get on treatment

138
00:08:30.900 --> 00:08:33.303
than to delay it and it get missed.

139
00:08:34.920 --> 00:08:38.400
Which of the following is a USPSTF's recommendation

140
00:08:38.400 --> 00:08:40.560
regarding daily supplementation of vitamin D

141
00:08:40.560 --> 00:08:44.703
and calcium for postmenopausal women to prevent fracture?

142
00:08:45.930 --> 00:08:47.433
A, not recommended,

143
00:08:49.380 --> 00:08:52.803
B, C, and D have different doses for you to choose from.

144
00:08:58.350 --> 00:09:01.390
And currently, it is not recommended

145
00:09:02.250 --> 00:09:05.913
to prevent fracture for primary prevention.

146
00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:08.880
If somebody does have osteoporosis,

147
00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:11.520
or they've had a fracture, and you start them on therapy

148
00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:14.070
with a bisphosphonate or Prolia or something like that,

149
00:09:14.070 --> 00:09:16.070
they should be on calcium and vitamin D.

150
00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:20.100
But just somebody who's going along in life fine

151
00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:21.690
and hadn't had any problems,

152
00:09:21.690 --> 00:09:23.440
the recommendation is not to do it.

153
00:09:24.750 --> 00:09:27.630
It's actually a D, potentially causing harm.

154
00:09:27.630 --> 00:09:30.750
The big thing was kidney stones.

155
00:09:30.750 --> 00:09:32.913
That's one of the factors causing problems.

156
00:09:35.220 --> 00:09:38.190
Insufficient evidence with higher doses,

157
00:09:38.190 --> 00:09:39.750
and they don't address, like we said,

158
00:09:39.750 --> 00:09:41.730
with women with osteoporosis,

159
00:09:41.730 --> 00:09:43.260
but if they're gonna be on treatment,

160
00:09:43.260 --> 00:09:45.420
they probably need supplementation,

161
00:09:45.420 --> 00:09:48.090
and here are things in our toolbox

162
00:09:48.090 --> 00:09:50.133
for treatment of osteoporosis.

163
00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:57.100
The ones with stars by them are anabolic agents

164
00:09:58.710 --> 00:10:00.420
to really aggressively rebuild

165
00:10:00.420 --> 00:10:03.270
and are approved for severe osteoporosis.

166
00:10:03.270 --> 00:10:06.300
Or maybe you've got somebody that's been on Alenddronate

167
00:10:06.300 --> 00:10:10.695
for four years and then they still have a fracture,

168
00:10:10.695 --> 00:10:13.050
consider one of those with a star.

169
00:10:13.050 --> 00:10:14.943
Also notice down at the bottom,

170
00:10:16.740 --> 00:10:21.740
Ibandronate and Raloxifene do nothing for femur fractures.

171
00:10:25.230 --> 00:10:27.570
They do something for compression fractures,

172
00:10:27.570 --> 00:10:30.363
vertebral fractures, but nothing for femur.

173
00:10:33.840 --> 00:10:35.280
I used to tell our residents

174
00:10:35.280 --> 00:10:39.543
that Sally Field used to do commercials for Boniva.

175
00:10:40.410 --> 00:10:43.890
Some of y'all remember that? Yeah, yeah.

176
00:10:43.890 --> 00:10:45.330
The medical students or residents

177
00:10:45.330 --> 00:10:47.130
don't know who that is anymore.

178
00:10:47.130 --> 00:10:48.830
I've had to stop using that story.

179
00:10:51.390 --> 00:10:55.560
Forrest Gump's mama, and then they're like, "Oh yeah, yeah."

180
00:10:55.560 --> 00:10:57.570
So bisphosphonates, empty stomach,

181
00:10:57.570 --> 00:11:00.360
full glass of water, sit up for 30 minutes.

182
00:11:00.360 --> 00:11:03.555
Contraindications, esophageal stricture, achalasia,

183
00:11:03.555 --> 00:11:08.555
if they can't sit upright, and then GFR calculations.

184
00:11:11.160 --> 00:11:13.440
Also remember this, if they've got hypocalcemia,

185
00:11:13.440 --> 00:11:15.690
you don't wanna give 'em a bisphosphonate.

186
00:11:15.690 --> 00:11:18.260
It's gonna make that calcium go lower.

187
00:11:18.260 --> 00:11:20.110
(audience member sneezes)
Bless you.

188
00:11:22.740 --> 00:11:24.210
Here's what everybody always asks about,

189
00:11:24.210 --> 00:11:25.890
what about jaw necrosis?

190
00:11:25.890 --> 00:11:27.450
I've got a friend who had jaw necrosis

191
00:11:27.450 --> 00:11:28.550
with a bisphosphonate.

192
00:11:29.546 --> 00:11:32.760
More often with IV bisphosphonates,

193
00:11:32.760 --> 00:11:35.060
you are more likely to get struck by lightning

194
00:11:36.660 --> 00:11:39.870
than to have jaw necrosis from a bisphosphonate.

195
00:11:39.870 --> 00:11:41.850
Also, as was pointed out earlier,

196
00:11:41.850 --> 00:11:43.920
the longer you're on a bisphosphonate,

197
00:11:43.920 --> 00:11:46.473
the higher these risk factors go up.

198
00:11:47.340 --> 00:11:50.940
That's why we cut them off for an oral bisphosphonate,

199
00:11:50.940 --> 00:11:52.503
typically five years.

200
00:11:55.285 --> 00:11:59.520
IV bisphosphonates, maybe three years.

201
00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:01.620
If it's really severe osteoporosis

202
00:12:01.620 --> 00:12:03.150
and you don't have any other options,

203
00:12:03.150 --> 00:12:07.830
you can double those, potentially do the IV for six years,

204
00:12:07.830 --> 00:12:11.108
maybe the oral for 10, but that's pushing it.

205
00:12:11.108 --> 00:12:13.041
You gotta be aware of the risk.

206
00:12:13.041 --> 00:12:15.000
Those risks go up the longer they're on it,

207
00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.523
especially the atypical femur fracture.

208
00:12:22.560 --> 00:12:23.550
So there you go.

209
00:12:23.550 --> 00:12:25.380
You still get the benefit of a bisphosphonate

210
00:12:25.380 --> 00:12:27.513
up to five years after you stop it.

211
00:12:29.190 --> 00:12:30.120
So you could stop it

212
00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:33.030
and give them a quote/unquote drug holiday.

213
00:12:33.030 --> 00:12:34.770
If maybe their insurance doesn't cover something,

214
00:12:34.770 --> 00:12:36.120
switch into something else,

215
00:12:37.260 --> 00:12:39.750
so you're still gonna get the benefit.

216
00:12:39.750 --> 00:12:41.580
Time to benefit is about a year.

217
00:12:41.580 --> 00:12:42.900
Obviously, if somebody's on hospice,

218
00:12:42.900 --> 00:12:45.690
limited life expectancy, they're not ambulatory anymore,

219
00:12:45.690 --> 00:12:47.040
it's reasonable to stop it.

220
00:12:49.470 --> 00:12:50.820
Which of the following has been shown

221
00:12:50.820 --> 00:12:52.290
to have an analgesic benefit

222
00:12:52.290 --> 00:12:54.393
in acute osteoporotic fractures?

223
00:13:00.098 --> 00:13:04.830
Yeah, calcitonin. Y'all were listening. Nice job, nice job!

224
00:13:04.830 --> 00:13:07.710
Intranasal, you do one spray, one side of the nostril.

225
00:13:07.710 --> 00:13:09.330
The next day, you do the other.

226
00:13:09.330 --> 00:13:11.820
We don't extend that longer than a few weeks,

227
00:13:11.820 --> 00:13:14.910
'cause we worry about increased cancer risk.

228
00:13:14.910 --> 00:13:16.710
That's the reason you limit it to about four days,

229
00:13:16.710 --> 00:13:18.603
I mean, excuse me, about four weeks.

230
00:13:21.390 --> 00:13:24.123
Raloxifene, we mentioned that earlier,

231
00:13:25.230 --> 00:13:27.633
does not decrease hip fracture risk.

232
00:13:30.360 --> 00:13:31.473
So remember that,

233
00:13:32.970 --> 00:13:37.970
would be way down on your list of osteoporosis treatments.

234
00:13:38.490 --> 00:13:40.890
Teriparatide, parathyroid hormone,

235
00:13:40.890 --> 00:13:44.223
this is for severe osteoporosis, daily injections,

236
00:13:45.690 --> 00:13:47.490
high risk, severe osteoporosis.

237
00:13:47.490 --> 00:13:49.500
Don't do it for longer than two years,

238
00:13:49.500 --> 00:13:51.573
because of the risk of osteosarcoma,

239
00:13:53.820 --> 00:13:55.173
also known as Forteo.

240
00:13:57.990 --> 00:14:02.990
Denosumab, typically bisphosphonates are our first line.

241
00:14:03.300 --> 00:14:05.430
It would be reasonable though to do Prolia

242
00:14:05.430 --> 00:14:07.477
as a first line potentially,

243
00:14:07.477 --> 00:14:10.440
every six months, sub-q injection.

244
00:14:10.440 --> 00:14:11.493
Here's the key.

245
00:14:13.020 --> 00:14:16.563
Once you stop using Prolia, you lose the benefit.

246
00:14:20.010 --> 00:14:22.080
Whereas bisphosphonates, you get a benefit

247
00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:26.520
extending still in their system for a few years.

248
00:14:26.520 --> 00:14:27.520
Prolia, you lose it,

249
00:14:28.410 --> 00:14:30.450
so you better have something ready to go.

250
00:14:30.450 --> 00:14:35.013
Also, about five-year, five-year length of treatment.

251
00:14:36.360 --> 00:14:40.083
So what do you do? Maybe you go bisphosphonate, then Prolia.

252
00:14:41.231 --> 00:14:44.520
Or maybe you do Prolia then a bisphosphonate.

253
00:14:44.520 --> 00:14:46.230
Maybe you consider after five years

254
00:14:46.230 --> 00:14:47.850
that bisphosphonate's gonna be out of their system,

255
00:14:47.850 --> 00:14:49.290
so you can do bisphosphonate, Prolia,

256
00:14:49.290 --> 00:14:50.880
then back to bisphosphonate.

257
00:14:50.880 --> 00:14:53.640
Maybe at that point the DEXA scans getting worse.

258
00:14:53.640 --> 00:14:56.730
I agree with Dr. Gary, about five years.

259
00:14:56.730 --> 00:14:59.460
I usually get DEXA scans about five years,

260
00:14:59.460 --> 00:15:01.710
about the time I'm about to switch treatment.

261
00:15:01.710 --> 00:15:03.570
There's a good AAFP article not long ago

262
00:15:03.570 --> 00:15:05.408
showing that really the benefits

263
00:15:05.408 --> 00:15:07.650
of doing DEXA scans more frequently

264
00:15:07.650 --> 00:15:10.000
than every three years doesn't do a darn thing.

265
00:15:12.390 --> 00:15:13.320
So you always have to ask yourself,

266
00:15:13.320 --> 00:15:14.870
is this gonna change what I do?

267
00:15:18.270 --> 00:15:20.190
Demented 70-year-old, widowed woman

268
00:15:20.190 --> 00:15:23.250
is admitted to your service, determined to lack capacity.

269
00:15:23.250 --> 00:15:24.933
There are no advanced directives.

270
00:15:25.800 --> 00:15:29.280
Who typically is next in line for decision making.

271
00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:31.620
The power of attorney appointed after admission,

272
00:15:31.620 --> 00:15:33.870
her fiancé of two years,

273
00:15:33.870 --> 00:15:37.443
her sister, or her 16-year-old grandson.

274
00:15:43.200 --> 00:15:44.670
Yeah, her sister.

275
00:15:44.670 --> 00:15:48.000
Can't appoint a power of attorney after admission.

276
00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:52.323
Fiancé has no legal bearing, and the 16-year-old is a minor,

277
00:15:54.150 --> 00:15:55.900
so it'd be the sister in this case.

278
00:15:56.790 --> 00:15:59.670
Ideally, we're all doing our advanced-care planning visits

279
00:15:59.670 --> 00:16:01.983
and making sure all these things are in place.

280
00:16:04.080 --> 00:16:06.570
Documented advanced directives.

281
00:16:06.570 --> 00:16:09.448
Different states are gonna have different rules.

282
00:16:09.448 --> 00:16:12.360
If you get a question about definitions,

283
00:16:12.360 --> 00:16:14.010
there you go for substituted judgment

284
00:16:14.010 --> 00:16:16.353
and the best-interest standard too.

285
00:16:17.460 --> 00:16:19.353
Sometimes questions like that pop up.

286
00:16:21.420 --> 00:16:22.980
All right, now we got a demented patient

287
00:16:22.980 --> 00:16:24.930
admitted for Sick Sinus Syndrome.

288
00:16:24.930 --> 00:16:27.030
Cardiologist recommends a pacemaker,

289
00:16:27.030 --> 00:16:29.070
and the patient refuses.

290
00:16:29.070 --> 00:16:30.210
You and the cardiologist

291
00:16:30.210 --> 00:16:31.770
explain the procedure to the patient

292
00:16:31.770 --> 00:16:34.560
and believes she understands the pros and cons.

293
00:16:34.560 --> 00:16:37.500
The daughter is the healthcare power of attorney

294
00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:40.053
and wants to proceed with the pacemaker placement.

295
00:16:41.430 --> 00:16:42.660
What are we gonna do?

296
00:16:42.660 --> 00:16:46.890
Proceed with the procedure, consult psychiatry,

297
00:16:46.890 --> 00:16:49.020
don't do the procedure,

298
00:16:49.020 --> 00:16:52.248
or don't trust the daughter, call the son.

299
00:16:52.248 --> 00:16:55.248
(audience laughing)

300
00:16:56.370 --> 00:16:58.820
So she's not gonna be the one to take care of me.

301
00:17:01.170 --> 00:17:03.540
In this case, we don't proceed with the procedure.

302
00:17:03.540 --> 00:17:05.250
Even though the person was demented,

303
00:17:05.250 --> 00:17:08.280
they still were able to repeat back the risks

304
00:17:08.280 --> 00:17:09.513
of the procedure.

305
00:17:11.040 --> 00:17:12.660
Just 'cause someone has dementia

306
00:17:12.660 --> 00:17:14.373
doesn't mean they lack capacity.

307
00:17:15.480 --> 00:17:17.790
Capacity is also very subjective.

308
00:17:17.790 --> 00:17:19.380
Somebody can have the capacity

309
00:17:19.380 --> 00:17:22.593
whether to have the chicken or the brisket for lunch,

310
00:17:24.420 --> 00:17:26.970
or to get the Mickey Mouse or the princess bandaid,

311
00:17:27.930 --> 00:17:31.443
but maybe not bigger decisions, so it's very subjective.

312
00:17:32.580 --> 00:17:34.950
Most states require two physicians

313
00:17:34.950 --> 00:17:37.530
to determine that someone lacks capacity.

314
00:17:37.530 --> 00:17:40.290
In a AAFP article, not long ago, they recommended,

315
00:17:40.290 --> 00:17:43.083
and this is the one I use, the Aid to Capacity Exam.

316
00:17:43.920 --> 00:17:45.397
It's gonna go through those questions like,

317
00:17:45.397 --> 00:17:47.017
"Do you understand what we're saying?

318
00:17:47.017 --> 00:17:50.373
"Can you repeat back the risks?" Those type of things.

319
00:17:52.230 --> 00:17:57.230
Key technical term, competency is determined by the courts.

320
00:17:57.300 --> 00:17:59.133
A judge gets involved with that.

321
00:18:00.390 --> 00:18:02.703
Physicians determine capacity.

322
00:18:04.477 --> 00:18:06.513
We don't determine competency.

323
00:18:09.870 --> 00:18:12.483
And American Bar Association has different things.

324
00:18:13.560 --> 00:18:14.393
High yield points,

325
00:18:14.393 --> 00:18:16.200
don't recommend percutaneous feeding tubes

326
00:18:16.200 --> 00:18:20.370
in people with dementia, causes all kinds of problems,

327
00:18:20.370 --> 00:18:22.230
agitation, doesn't improve outcomes.

328
00:18:22.230 --> 00:18:24.030
You just make the patient miserable.

329
00:18:24.930 --> 00:18:27.060
That is part of the disease process and totally okay.

330
00:18:27.060 --> 00:18:28.200
The person's gonna be comfortable.

331
00:18:28.200 --> 00:18:29.600
They're not gonna be hungry.

332
00:18:30.810 --> 00:18:32.760
The brain is shutting off, that's okay.

333
00:18:35.820 --> 00:18:37.803
Don't use appetite stimulants.

334
00:18:39.660 --> 00:18:43.863
On the Beers Criteria is to avoid megestrol.

335
00:18:44.850 --> 00:18:46.550
I still see it every now and then.

336
00:18:47.820 --> 00:18:50.520
Don't use it, 'cause it kills people and causes clots.

337
00:18:52.290 --> 00:18:54.633
We like to not kill people. Don't use it.

338
00:18:55.560 --> 00:18:57.810
Most of these things are evidence for appetite simulates.

339
00:18:57.810 --> 00:18:59.343
They don't really work anyway.

340
00:19:01.050 --> 00:19:03.257
Somebody's gonna ask, "Well, what do you do?"

341
00:19:04.620 --> 00:19:06.820
We try to give the patient things they like.

342
00:19:07.860 --> 00:19:09.810
If they're depressed, maybe mirtazapine

343
00:19:09.810 --> 00:19:11.960
or something like that could be beneficial.

344
00:19:13.140 --> 00:19:14.940
Ultimately, this is a lot of education

345
00:19:14.940 --> 00:19:17.163
and not a lot of great tools in our toolbox.

346
00:19:19.770 --> 00:19:23.640
I also, like Dr. Vail, had something earlier

347
00:19:23.640 --> 00:19:25.200
about people with gastric bypass,

348
00:19:25.200 --> 00:19:27.930
you encourage them to eat protein first.

349
00:19:27.930 --> 00:19:30.840
I would say the same thing in older adults.

350
00:19:30.840 --> 00:19:32.220
If you're gonna be limited on your intake,

351
00:19:32.220 --> 00:19:33.900
really make sure you get the protein

352
00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:35.373
to maintain your muscle mass.

353
00:19:36.990 --> 00:19:38.850
All right, 87-year-old progressive decline,

354
00:19:38.850 --> 00:19:41.340
baseline mental status, has anorexia, constipation,

355
00:19:41.340 --> 00:19:44.010
intermittent nausea, 10-pound weight loss.

356
00:19:44.010 --> 00:19:46.110
More recently, she became nonverbal,

357
00:19:46.110 --> 00:19:49.260
unable to ambulate at all and using a wheelchair,

358
00:19:49.260 --> 00:19:52.473
disoriented and intermittently incontinent of urine.

359
00:19:53.970 --> 00:19:58.470
On exam, affect is flat, mucus membranes dry,

360
00:19:58.470 --> 00:20:03.423
irregular pulse of 105, otherwise unremarkable.

361
00:20:04.410 --> 00:20:08.973
Pretty lethargic, large decline, now how's that pulse?

362
00:20:11.730 --> 00:20:13.590
Which is the following is the most likely cause

363
00:20:13.590 --> 00:20:15.540
of this patient's symptoms?

364
00:20:15.540 --> 00:20:20.283
UTI, hypothyroidism, elder abuse, or hyperthyroidism?

365
00:20:25.800 --> 00:20:27.800
Yeah, look at that, 25% still picked it.

366
00:20:28.680 --> 00:20:32.181
This could actually be hyperthyroidism,

367
00:20:32.181 --> 00:20:34.037
which can present differently in older adults,

368
00:20:34.037 --> 00:20:36.873
and it could be apathetic thyrotoxicosis,

369
00:20:37.710 --> 00:20:40.590
could have that lethargy, weight loss, constipation,

370
00:20:40.590 --> 00:20:43.710
but you still have some of the hyperthyroidism symptoms,

371
00:20:43.710 --> 00:20:46.803
like AFib and weight loss.

372
00:20:49.140 --> 00:20:50.580
So this could be a little paradoxical

373
00:20:50.580 --> 00:20:52.080
from what we typically expect.

374
00:20:53.880 --> 00:20:56.070
Don't recommend screening breast, colorectal, prostate,

375
00:20:56.070 --> 00:20:58.870
lung cancer without considering life expectancy

376
00:21:00.180 --> 00:21:02.970
and the risks of potentially...

377
00:21:02.970 --> 00:21:04.770
There's things that we do to screen.

378
00:21:06.180 --> 00:21:08.523
There's USPSTF recommendations.

379
00:21:11.370 --> 00:21:15.780
For the gray area there for our colorectal and mammography,

380
00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:17.130
like Dr. Weiss Miller mentioned earlier,

381
00:21:17.130 --> 00:21:18.813
the mammography is being updated.

382
00:21:20.735 --> 00:21:22.260
What to consider is,

383
00:21:22.260 --> 00:21:25.740
do I think this person's gonna be alive 10 years from now?

384
00:21:25.740 --> 00:21:27.900
If you think they are,

385
00:21:27.900 --> 00:21:32.900
then colorectal and mammography are probably worth doing.

386
00:21:33.720 --> 00:21:35.010
There's a tool you can plug in,

387
00:21:35.010 --> 00:21:36.903
which is validated Eprognosis.

388
00:21:37.770 --> 00:21:39.750
You can plug in the patient's characteristics,

389
00:21:39.750 --> 00:21:40.583
and it will tell you,

390
00:21:40.583 --> 00:21:42.090
you can pull it up in the room with a patient,

391
00:21:42.090 --> 00:21:43.590
whether they should get screened or not.

392
00:21:43.590 --> 00:21:47.970
It'll say very clear, more risk, more benefit,

393
00:21:47.970 --> 00:21:49.800
and you can talk about it.

394
00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:50.700
It's a great tool.

395
00:21:55.020 --> 00:21:57.363
Y'all went through stress testing already.

396
00:21:58.890 --> 00:22:01.110
The common one, that cataract surgery question.

397
00:22:01.110 --> 00:22:05.160
Y'all get that, right? You just had a whole lecture on this.

398
00:22:05.160 --> 00:22:06.840
Elder abuse, this is gonna be one of those things

399
00:22:06.840 --> 00:22:08.190
you look for the buzzwords.

400
00:22:10.530 --> 00:22:13.200
Also being updated from the USPSTF

401
00:22:13.200 --> 00:22:14.550
whether to screen for this.

402
00:22:16.830 --> 00:22:18.330
You're gonna have in your question stem,

403
00:22:18.330 --> 00:22:19.620
that's gonna be poor health,

404
00:22:19.620 --> 00:22:22.173
low socioeconomic status, dementia.

405
00:22:23.541 --> 00:22:26.943
Let's acknowledge too, caregiving is incredibly hard.

406
00:22:31.080 --> 00:22:35.163
It's a big problem for us, big problem.

407
00:22:38.520 --> 00:22:40.290
There's some more question STEM things.

408
00:22:40.290 --> 00:22:45.290
I mean these new dementia treatments

409
00:22:45.810 --> 00:22:48.453
that got approved that cost $26,000 a year,

410
00:22:50.820 --> 00:22:55.140
which I could go on and on about my concerns about them.

411
00:22:55.140 --> 00:22:57.330
Then the average social security check in the US

412
00:22:57.330 --> 00:22:58.923
is about 1,500 bucks a month.

413
00:23:01.740 --> 00:23:03.840
So, we make decisions on where our resources are.

414
00:23:03.840 --> 00:23:05.250
Caregiving is incredibly hard,

415
00:23:05.250 --> 00:23:07.050
and this ain't gonna get any easier.

416
00:23:08.280 --> 00:23:10.530
All right, which medication's least likely to be associated

417
00:23:10.530 --> 00:23:11.830
with erectile dysfunction?

418
00:23:13.020 --> 00:23:13.853
Remember what I said?

419
00:23:13.853 --> 00:23:15.030
I tell all the medical students,

420
00:23:15.030 --> 00:23:16.890
they can always just say to all my questions,

421
00:23:16.890 --> 00:23:18.960
anticholinergic symptoms.

422
00:23:18.960 --> 00:23:21.023
You can use that to think about this one too.

423
00:23:26.040 --> 00:23:29.070
Yeah, Losartan, HCTZ is a diuretic.

424
00:23:29.070 --> 00:23:31.820
The others are gonna have some anticholinergic effects.

425
00:23:33.270 --> 00:23:35.313
There's your causes of ED in order,

426
00:23:36.840 --> 00:23:38.283
most commonly vascular.

427
00:23:41.010 --> 00:23:43.593
And almost, let's wrap up here.

428
00:23:45.090 --> 00:23:47.940
Oh, here we go, greater than 100,000 e. coli.

429
00:23:47.940 --> 00:23:49.500
You should prescribe antimicrobials

430
00:23:49.500 --> 00:23:54.340
if the IDSA has good guidelines on this.

431
00:23:55.350 --> 00:23:58.143
And also, if you wanna write down something to look up,

432
00:23:58.143 --> 00:24:01.510
it's been validated, it's the McGeer Criteria

433
00:24:02.760 --> 00:24:05.733
for older adults that live in residential care.

434
00:24:11.040 --> 00:24:14.190
If there's not specific urinary tract symptoms present

435
00:24:14.190 --> 00:24:18.843
of which confusion alone is not a symptom, it's not a UTI.

436
00:24:20.910 --> 00:24:21.993
Don't use my, here it is,

437
00:24:21.993 --> 00:24:24.450
from the AGS too, "Choosing Wisely."

438
00:24:24.450 --> 00:24:25.920
Don't use antimicrobials

439
00:24:25.920 --> 00:24:28.270
unless there's specific urinary tract symptoms.

440
00:24:29.520 --> 00:24:31.203
Urgent incontinence, big problem,

441
00:24:32.040 --> 00:24:35.916
medicines only work in about 30% of folks.

442
00:24:35.916 --> 00:24:37.770
I underlined the safer ones,

443
00:24:37.770 --> 00:24:40.050
the least anticholinergic options

444
00:24:40.050 --> 00:24:41.820
and treatment for urgent incontinence.

445
00:24:41.820 --> 00:24:43.350
Beta 3 agonists are reasonable,

446
00:24:43.350 --> 00:24:46.290
'cause they don't cross the blood-brain barrier too.

447
00:24:46.290 --> 00:24:48.630
And then don't forget pelvic muscle exercises,

448
00:24:48.630 --> 00:24:49.563
bladder training.

449
00:24:52.080 --> 00:24:53.700
And here's some high-yield stuff.

450
00:24:53.700 --> 00:24:57.000
Weight loss is effective for stress incontinence for men.

451
00:24:57.000 --> 00:24:58.950
Make sure you're checking post void residual

452
00:24:58.950 --> 00:25:01.020
before starting meds for incontinence,

453
00:25:01.020 --> 00:25:03.240
like some of those antimuscarinics.

454
00:25:03.240 --> 00:25:05.403
Make sure they're not holding onto urine,

455
00:25:06.510 --> 00:25:08.160
or you'll cause a problem.

456
00:25:08.160 --> 00:25:10.920
And then you got really demented folks with incontinence.

457
00:25:10.920 --> 00:25:13.950
Encourage them to do frequent bathroom trips.

458
00:25:13.950 --> 00:25:15.990
And there's my answers,

459
00:25:15.990 --> 00:25:17.310
and I'll be back again in a little while.

460
00:25:17.310 --> 00:25:19.470
Send your questions. Thank y'all.

461
00:25:19.470 --> 00:25:20.933
